          "body": "The chapter opens with the word 'ach' — brother, countryman — and repeats it six times in four verses. The repetition is not stylistic padding; it establishes the relational matrix within which all the laws function. Israel is not a collection of autonomous individuals but a covenant family whose members bear legal obligations to one another. The prohibition against 'alam' — hiding oneself, looking away — is striking. The law does not merely require action; it forbids the psychological posture of studied ignorance. To see your neighbor's ox straying and deliberately avert your gaze is itself a transgression. The obligation to return lost property and to help a fallen animal extends to all lost items ('anything lost by your countryman,' v. 3), resisting any attempt to narrow the duty to convenient categories. This section anticipates the Sermon on the Mount's demand for neighbor-love that extends beyond natural inclination (Matthew 5:43–48) and the Good Samaritan's refusal to walk on the other side (Luke 10:31–32). The Mosaic law and Jesus's exposition share the same root: the neighbor's need creates a claim on me that I may not ignore."
