          "title": "Creation-order laws — distinctions that must not be mixed (vv. 5–12)",
          "body": "Verses 5–12 are the chapter's most theologically compressed section and its most frequently misread. Six laws in eight verses cover gender-specific clothing (v. 5), the mother bird (vv. 6–7), the house parapet (v. 8), mixed seeds in a vineyard (v. 9), mixed-species plowing (v. 10), mixed-fiber garments (v. 11), and tassels on the garment's four corners (v. 12). What unifies them is the concept of *kilayim* (mixing of kinds, v. 9) and the broader creational theology of Genesis 1, where God creates by separating and distinguishing. The repeated 'you shall not mix' points to the theological claim that the distinctions God built into creation — between kinds, between species, between male and female — are not accidents of culture but features of divinely ordered reality. The gender-clothing law (v. 5) receives the chapter's strongest evaluative word: *toevah*, abomination. Christopher Wright (*Deuteronomy*, NIBC, 1996) argues this law targets cultic cross-dressing associated with Canaanite fertility rites, not merely sartorial preference — though the broader principle of gender-distinction is canonical (Genesis 1:27; Matthew 19:4). The mother-bird law (vv. 6–7) is the chapter's most surprising item: it restricts the taking of a bird in a way that preserves the reproductive source. It carries the same covenant promise ('that it may be well with you and that you may prolong your days') as the Fifth Commandment (Deuteronomy 5:16). The Talmud will later observe that if God attaches such promises to a law as minor as releasing a bird, how much more to weightier laws — the very *qal va-homer* logic Jesus himself uses (Matthew 10:29–31). The tassel-law (v. 12) closes the section by turning the garment into a mnemonic — a visible reminder of covenant identity at every moment of the day (cf. Numbers 15:38–40). The garment that must not be mixed (v. 11) is the same garment whose corners must be marked by tassels of covenant fidelity (v. 12)."
