          "title": "The garment as unifying symbol (vv. 3, 5, 11–12, 17, 30)",
          "body": "A thread that runs through the chapter without being announced is the *simlah* — the outer garment. It appears as lost property to be returned (v. 3), as the object of gender-crossing prohibition (v. 5), as the mixed-fiber textile prohibited (v. 11), as the object of tassel-commandment (v. 12), as the virginity cloth presented before the elders (v. 17), and as the 'skirt' (*kanaph*, the same word as 'corner' in v. 12) the son must not uncover (v. 30). The garment in the ancient Near East was not merely clothing — it represented identity, honor, and covenant status. A man's skirt uncovering his wife was a metaphor for the covenant of marriage (cf. Ruth 3:9; Ezekiel 16:8). The tokens of virginity on the garment (v. 17) were displayed publicly because honor, in a covenant community, is a public good. The tassels on the garment's corners (v. 12) marked the wearer as bound by covenant obligations. To mix the garment's fibers (v. 11) was to confuse the symbol of covenant identity. To take another's garment to cross-dress (v. 5) was to blur the creator's distinctions. The chapter uses a single physical object — cloth — as a lens through which neighbor-duty, creation-order, and sexual covenant all come into view. The garment is the chapter's silent organizing metaphor."
